<h2>
    Boat and Drift Fishing Opportunities
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Clackamas River</strong>: Drift boat sections between Barton and Carver.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Sandy River</strong>: Side-drift from Dodge Park or Dabney.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Columbia River</strong>: Launch at Troutdale or Scappoose for main-channel drift.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    Always monitor flows and carry PFDs. Aligning your drift with current seams is key to hooking steelhead.
</p>
<h2>
    Gear and Setup for Northwest Steelhead
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Rods</strong>: 8’6”–10’6” medium-action spinning or baitcasting rods.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Line</strong>: 10–15 lb braid or mono with 8–12 lb fluorocarbon leaders.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Reels</strong>: Smooth drag systems sized 2500–4000+.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Terminal Tackle</strong>: Size 2–4 single hooks, 1–3 oz sinkers, fluorocarbon shock tippets.
    </li>
</ul>
<p>
    For fly anglers, use 7–8 wt rods with sink tips or floating lines based on water depth.
</p>
<h2>
    Baits, Lures &amp; Techniques That Work
</h2>
<ol>
    <li>
        <strong>Drift Fishing</strong>: Roe clusters, yarnies, and cured eggs under float.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Plug/Bobbing</strong>: Side-drifting small plugs like Kwikfish on low-water bites.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Hardware</strong>: Spinners (Blue Fox, Panther Martin) and spoons (Little Cleo).
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Fly Fishing</strong>: Swing egg patterns, leeches, and intruder-style flies in runs and pools.
    </li>
</ol>
<h2>
    Fly Fishing for Steelhead Near Hillsboro
</h2>
<p>
    Detroit tips:
</p>
<ul>
    <li>
        Use <strong>7–8 wt rods</strong>, 9–12 ft leaders, and sinking-tip lines in deeper runs.
    </li>
    <li>
        Flies to carry: <strong>Glo Bugs</strong>, <strong>worm patterns</strong>, <strong>intruder/spey flies</strong>, <strong>egg-sucking leeches</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
        Best dry presentation zones include <strong>Clackamas tail-outs</strong>, <strong>Sandy flats</strong>, and calmer <strong>Columbia eddies</strong>.
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Regulation &amp; Licensing Overview
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Oregon Angling License</strong> and <strong>Combined Angling Tag</strong> required.
    </li>
    <li>
        Only <strong>clipped adipose fin fish</strong> (hatchery steelhead) may be kept unless exceptions apply.
    </li>
    <li>
        Seasonal regulations and barbless-hook rules vary—check <strong>ODFW’s current regulations</strong>.
    </li>
    <li>
        Measure flow, monitor closure updates online, and respect catch-and-release markers.
    </li>
</ul>
